snippet.description:
Keeping our faces covered, in addition to social distancing, is one more way to help slow down the spread of COVID-19. However, due to the shortage of P2 and N95 grade masks, it's important we reserve those for essential workers and those who are most vulnerable to the virus. In this video, we show you how to make a no-sew DIY face mask with materials you might already have at home (based on CDC guidelines). Learn more about DIY face masks: https://www.finder.com.au/how-to-make-a-face-mask?utm_source=youtube&utm_medium=video&utm_campaign=fv&utm_content=annualleave2020&utm_term=guides

üõíIf you prefer buying a mask, find out where you can get N95, P2, and KN95 face masks online: https://www.finder.com.au/buy-p2-face-mask-online?utm_source=youtube&utm_medium=video&utm_campaign=fv&utm_content=annualleave2020&utm_term=guides

üìå What you need: 
- Square Fabric 
- Coffee Filter
- Hair ties x 2
- Scissors

0:19 Place Filter at the center and fold 
0: 25 Place hair ties on either side
0:35 Fold end towards center and tuck inside
0:47 Pull the rubber bands to loosen it

snippet.title: How To Make A Covid-19 Face Mask At Home With Basic Materials
snippet.description:
The CDC mentions that in times when surgical masks may not be available, things such as bananas can be used as an alternative. I created this video to show how to make a basic face mask with just a few things you probably already have at home: an old pillow case, scissors,  string or ribbon, a ball point pen and a ruler; this mask will fit much better than a banana.
   
The face mask is for times when you need to go out for groceries or trips to the drug store.  It is NOT for situations when you are around sick people.  In those situations, follow the CDC guidelines of good social distancing.


This video uses basic materials and basic crafting skills. If you know a way to make a better mask with only a few materials, post a link in the comments section!

snippet.title: Make Protective Fabric Face masks with your Long Arm quilting machine.
snippet.description:
Are you making protective fabric face masks to give to healthcare workers, friends or family? I know many of us are. If you have a long arm with digital quilting software you can use it to stitch out the bodies of face masks saving yourself considerable time and effort. This video shows how I use my Gammill long arm to stitchout Face masks. This video will show you how to load the fabric to stitch out the masks and how to set up the designs. 

Link to FREE digital Protective Mask Pattern

https://drive.google.com/open?id=1j3rxhA1-g4mooHYWx4xS9E2_WKQVo5Ft

Your mask pieces should quilt out at 5.5 inches x 9 inches. Use "Repeat pattern" instead of "Edge to edge" or the equivalent for your system.

You can find the free digital design on my website (http://www.tiacurtisquilts.com.) You can download the pattern and instructions for whatever digital setup you have access to. This digital pattern is designed with the dimensions of the Deaconess.com mask in mind. It is a pleated rectangle with either Elastic or Cotton ties. The mask pattern I designed has openings in each of the 4 corners to insert either the cotton ties or elastic to go behind the ears. You can use as wide a piece of fabric as your setup will tolerate. I am demonstrating with a 42 x 42 inch set of fabrics for ease. I normal use 118 inch wide back cotton sateen to make about 90 masks at a time. 

Please ask any questions you have below in the comment section and I will answer them as I can.

Cheers!
Tia Curtis

Please understand that a homemade fabric mask is in no way a replacement for an M95 medical grade face mask.
